## CI Container Usage

### GitHub Actions Example

```yaml
services:
  postgres:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    env:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: test
      POSTGRES_DB: ecommerce_test
    options: >-
      --health-cmd pg_isready
      --health-interval 10s
      --health-timeout 5s
      --health-retries 5

steps:
  - name: Run migrations
    run: alembic upgrade head
    env:
      DATABASE_URL: postgresql+asyncpg://postgres:test@localhost/ecommerce_test
  - name: Run tests
    run: pytest
```

Run migrations before tests in CI.

---

## Production Deployment

### Resource Limits

| Service | CPU | Memory |
|---------|-----|--------|
| API | 1 core (request 0.5) | 512MB–1GB |
| Web | 1 core | 512MB–1GB |
| PostgreSQL | 2+ cores | 4GB+ (managed service preferred) |

Set limits to prevent noisy neighbor issues.

### Scaling

- API: horizontal scaling behind load balancer (stateless)
- Web: horizontal scaling (stateless)
- PostgreSQL: vertical scaling or managed service with read replicas

### Health Endpoints

```
GET /health       — liveness (process alive)
GET /health/ready — readiness (DB connected, dependencies OK)
```

Orchestrator uses readiness for traffic routing.

---

## Security

- Non-root container user
- Read-only root filesystem where possible
- No SSH into containers — use orchestrator exec for debug
- Scan images for vulnerabilities (Trivy, Snyk) in CI
- Private container registry
- Network policies: API → PostgreSQL only, not public internet to DB

---

## Logging

- Log to stdout/stderr (12-factor app)
- Orchestrator collects logs (CloudWatch, Datadog, etc.)
- JSON structured logging in production
- No log files inside containers

---

## Database in Production

Prefer managed PostgreSQL (RDS, Cloud SQL, Supabase):

- Automated backups and PITR
- Patch management
- High availability

Do not run PostgreSQL in container in production unless team has DBA expertise and backup automation.

---

## Local Development Workflow

```bash
# Start dependencies
docker compose up -d postgres redis

# Run API natively (hot reload)
cd apps/api && uvicorn src.main:app --reload

# Run web natively
cd apps/web && npm run dev

# Run migrations
cd apps/api && alembic upgrade head

# Tear down
docker compose down        # keep data
docker compose down -v     # remove volumes
```

---

## Anti-Patterns

- `latest` tag in production
- Secrets in Dockerfile ENV or compose committed files
- Running as root in production container
- No health checks
- Giant monolithic image with dev dependencies included
- Database data in container without named volume
- Manual `docker exec` schema changes bypassing Alembic

